# Set/Get Network Interface (Adapter) Metric (Priority/Order) @ PowerShell
    REF: https://www.windowscentral.com/how-change-priority-order-network-adapters-windows-10

    ## Get
    
        PS> Get-NetIPInterface

        ifIndex InterfaceAlias                  AddressFamily NlMtu(Bytes) InterfaceMetric Dhcp     ConnectionState PolicyStore
        ------- --------------                  ------------- ------------ --------------- ----     --------------- -----------
        4       vEthernet (External Switch)     IPv6                  1500              25 Enabled  Connected       ActiveStore
        26      vEthernet (Default Switch)      IPv6                  1500            5000 Enabled  Connected       ActiveStore
        1       Loopback Pseudo-Interface 1     IPv6            4294967295              75 Disabled Connected       ActiveStore
        4       vEthernet (External Switch)     IPv4                  1500              25 Enabled  Connected       ActiveStore
        26      vEthernet (Default Switch)      IPv4                  1500            5000 Disabled Connected       ActiveStore
        1       Loopback Pseudo-Interface 1     IPv4            4294967295              75 Disabled Connected       ActiveStore


    ## Set (lower Metric-number is higher priority)
    
        PS> Set-NetIPInterface -InterfaceIndex 7 -InterfaceMetric 100

        ## Reset to Automatic 
        PS> Set-NetIPInterface -InterfaceIndex 7 -AutomaticMetric enabled


# Two-Factor Authentication

    ## Command

        NET USER "user name" /WORKSTATIONS: TrustedSystem1, TrustedSystem2

        @ XPC :: Restrict RDC/RDP access ...

            NET USER "XPC Remote" /WORKSTATIONS:HTPC
            NET USER "%USERNAME%" /WORKSTATIONS:XPC

        @ HTPC :: Restrict RDC/RDP access ...

            NET USER "Remote" /WORKSTATIONS:XPC
            NET USER "%USERNAME%" /WORKSTATIONS:HTPC



        @ XPC :: drive/folder Shares ... 

            Properties > Security > "Group or user names"
            
                > Add: SYSTEM, Administrators, and LAN  (Remove all others)
                
            Properties > Sharing > "Advanced Sharing" > Permissions 
            
                > Add: LAN  (Remove all others)
            

    ## Background
    
        NET USER - use it to limit login location to specific machines [Trusted System X]

        /WORKSTATIONS:{computername[,...] | *}
        Lists as many as eight computers from which a user can log on to the network. If the /WORKSTATIONS option has no list or if the list is *, the user can log on from any computer.

        Use to prevent a weak-password admin account, "Local", from remotely accessing its own [admin]shares; restrict its workstations to the local machine only.

        LAN [Admin]Shares/RDC/RDP Scenarios: 
        ------------------------------------
        1. Strong security for LAN [admin]shares & RDC/RDP access: Create Username "Remote" w/ strong passsord @ remote machine serving LAN [admin]shares. Restrict net-user-workstations of Remote to that local machine and machines on LAN from which Remote user is trusted to access those [admin]shares. Create group "LAN", making Remote a  member, and set access to shares, to LAN group ONLY, using Security & Sharing [tabs] using folder Properties applet. Restrict workstations for weak-password account [e.g., Username "Local"] to local-machine ONLY, and exclude Local from LAN group membership. Thus, Local admin account, w/ weak-password, is prohibited from remotely accessing even its own admin-shares.

        2. Strong security for RDC/RDP access by weak-password account: Say Username "Local" has weak password, and Username "Remote" has strong password. Set "/Workstations:" for Local to local-machine ONLY, and for Remote to remote-machine[s] ONLY. This will allow Remote to RDC/RDP into local-machine logon-screen, but disallow logon, causing logon-screen query for another user to logon, whereof Local can logon; SESSIONNAME=Console, not @ "RDP-Tcp#0". Yet Local is unable to remotely access local-machine via RDC/RDP, without Remote. Thus, Remote can be a shell admin [admin-shares] account; needn't install programs, adjust setup Desktop settings, curate Start Menu, etc.


    ## REF: http://support.microsoft.com/kb/251394